  "prompt": "Why is oxalic acid soluble in water?",
  "response": "Oxalic acid (HOOC-COOH) is soluble in water due to several key factors:\n\n1. Hydrogen bonding\n- Oxalic acid contains two carboxyl groups (-COOH)\n- These groups can form hydrogen bonds with water molecules\n- Hydrogen bonding allows the acid to interact strongly with water\n\n2. Polarity\n- Oxalic acid is a polar molecule\n- The carboxyl groups create areas of partial positive and negative charge\n- These polar regions can interact with water's polar molecules\n\n3. Molecular structure\n- The small molecular size facilitates water interaction\n- The presence of multiple oxygen atoms enables hydrogen bonding\n\n4. Dissociation\n- Oxalic acid can dissociate into ions in water\n- This further increases its solubility by creating charged species\n\n5. Hydration\n- Water molecules can surround and stabilize oxalic acid molecules\n- This process helps break intermolecular forces within the acid\n\nThese characteristics allow oxalic acid to readily dissolve in water, with solubility around 10% at room temperature. The strong interactions between oxalic acid and water molecules overcome the acid's internal molecular forces, resulting in good water solubility.",
